adding h1-h6 values to wordpress theme.json
To add individual styles for H1-H6 headings in your WordPress theme.json, you must define them within the elements section of the styles object. 
WordPress Developer Resources
WordPress Developer Resources
 +1
Implementation Structure
You can apply global styles to all headings using the heading element, or target specific levels (H1, H2, etc.) individually to override those defaults. 
groundworx.dev
groundworx.dev
 +1
json
{
  "version": 3,
  "styles": {
    "elements": {
      "heading": {
        "typography": {
          "fontFamily": "var(--wp--preset--font-family--sans-serif)",
          "fontWeight": "700"
        }
      },
      "h1": {
        "typography": {
          "fontSize": "var(--wp--preset--font-size--7-xl)",
          "lineHeight": "1.2"
        },
        "spacing": {
          "margin": { "top": "2rem", "bottom": "1rem" }
        }
      },
      "h2": {
        "typography": {
          "fontSize": "var(--wp--preset--font-size--6-xl)"
        }
      }
      // Repeat for h3 through h6 as needed
    }
  }
}
Use code with caution.

Key Considerations
The elements Key: This is where you target specific HTML tags like h1 through h6.
Specificity & Overrides: Styles defined in elements.h1 will override styles defined in the broader elements.heading.
Block Overrides: Be aware that if you apply styles directly to the core/heading block (under styles.blocks.core/heading), those may override your element-level styles in certain contexts within the editor.
Using Presets: It is best practice to reference your font sizes and families using CSS variables (e.g., var(--wp--preset--font-size--huge)) defined in the settings section of your theme.json. 
