typically I have a no margin approach to styling, but for headings and paragraph it makes sense. Where else is margin useful, the button of lists? maybe provide me with a number of margin suggestions for adding to my block styles
In a "no margin" or "reset" approach, adding specific margins to select blocks is essential for vertical rhythm—the visual flow and "breathing room" between content.
While headings and paragraphs are the most common, here are several other blocks where purposeful margins prevent a "cluttered" look:
1. Lists (core/list)
Lists often need a left margin to ensure bullets or numbers are properly indented, especially if you've reset global margins to zero.
Recommendation: Add a left margin (e.g., 1.5rem) to ensure visibility and a bottom margin (e.g., 1rem) to separate the list from the following block.
2. Buttons (core/buttons or core/button)
Buttons often sit too close to the text above them, especially if they are call-to-action (CTA) elements.
Recommendation: Add a top margin (e.g., 1.5rem) to create a clear "break" between descriptive text and the action button.
3. Quotes and Pullquotes (core/quote)
Quotes are meant to stand out. Without margins, they blend into the surrounding body text, losing their impact.
Recommendation: Use symmetrical top and bottom margins (e.g., 2rem) to frame the quote as a distinct "interruptor" in the layout.
4. Separators (core/separator)
Separators often have very small default margins, which can make them look like they are touching the blocks above or below.
Recommendation: Increase the vertical margins (top/bottom) to at least 2rem to make the section break feel intentional.
5. Media & Text (core/media-text)
When stacking these blocks, they can feel "heavy."
Recommendation: Add a bottom margin (e.g., var:preset|spacing|70) to ensure subsequent sections don't start immediately after the image ends.
Implementation in theme.json
Since you are using version 3, you should add these to the styles.blocks section of your file:
json
"styles": {
    "blocks": {
        "core/list": {
            "spacing": {
                "margin": { "left": "1.5rem", "bottom": "1.2rem" }
            }
        },
        "core/buttons": {
            "spacing": {
                "margin": { "top": "2rem" }
            }
        },
        "core/quote": {
            "spacing": {
                "margin": { "top": "3rem", "bottom": "3rem" }
            }
        }
    }
}
Use code with caution.

Pro Tip: Consider using blockGap (defined in styles.spacing.blockGap) as your primary tool for spacing between most blocks. It acts as a universal margin that only applies between blocks, preventing the need for individual "last-child" margin resets.
