Would you like to see how to configure blockGap to handle most of your spacing automatically while keeping your "no margin" philosophy
Since you prefer a no-margin philosophy, blockGap is your best friend. It acts like a CSS gap for the vertical flow of your site, adding space between blocks without adding "dead air" at the top of the first block or the bottom of the last. 
By using blockGap, you can keep your global margins at 0 and let the system handle the spacing dynamically. 
1. Define Global blockGap
In your styles object, you already have blockGap: "1.2rem". This ensures that every block (paragraphs, headings, images) has exactly 1.2rem of space between them automatically. 
2. Block-Specific blockGap
Some blocks, like Buttons or Columns, might need tighter or wider spacing between their internal child elements. You can override the global gap for specific blocks: 
json
"styles": {
    "spacing": {
        "blockGap": "1.5rem" 
    },
    "blocks": {
        "core/buttons": {
            "spacing": {
                "blockGap": "0.75rem"
            }
        },
        "core/social-links": {
            "spacing": {
                "blockGap": "0.5rem"
            }
        },
        "core/navigation": {
            "spacing": {
                "blockGap": "1rem"
            }
        }
    }
}
Use code with caution.

3. Handling "The Exception" (The Paragraph)
Even with a strict blockGap approach, Paragraphs often benefit from a bottom margin to distinguish "body flow" from "structural flow" (like a paragraph followed by a large image). 
If you find blockGap isn't enough for text-heavy areas, you can add a surgical margin just to the paragraph:
json
"core/paragraph": {
    "spacing": {
        "margin": { "bottom": "1rem" }
    }
}
Use code with caution.

Why this fits your style:
Cleaner DOM: You won't have to fight margin-top on the first element of a container.
Consistency: Every section of your site will feel mathematically aligned because the "gap" is a constant variable. 
